{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"58c021fb-cd5b-402d-9d7c-ce75f71bb12c","content":"For .NET 8 on Windows with admin access, use **dotnet-trace** — it's the simplest and most targeted tool.\n\n### Install & Collect\n\n```powershell\n# Install (once)\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n\n# Find your process ID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect a CPU profile (30 seconds is usually enough)\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can open in **Visual Studio** (Diagnostics Hub) or **PerfView**.\n\n### If you need OS-level detail too\n\nUse **PerfView** directly — it captures both .NET and kernel CPU stacks:\n\n```powershell\n# Download PerfView.exe from https://github.com/microsoft/perfview/releases\nPerfView.exe collect -ThreadTime -Duration:30\n```\n\n### Quick comparison\n\n| Tool | Best for | Overhead |\n|---|---|---|\n| `dotnet-trace` | Managed code hotpaths | Very low |\n| PerfView | Mixed managed + native + kernel | Low-medium |\n\n**Recommendation:** Start with `dotnet-trace` — it's lightweight, doesn't require a reboot, and gives you flame graphs of where CPU time is spent. Escalate to PerfView if you suspect native/kernel contention.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"056ff173-b9f7-423e-a4da-03988aa7f4f8","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about collecting a CPU trace for a .NET 8 service on Windows Server. This is a diagnostic/troubleshooting question, not a code change request. I can answer this from knowledge without needing to explore any codebase.","outputTokens":395,"requestId":"F88B:203D52:5187FE6:59CC1D6:69F9FDBE"},"id":"67c6fa62-2320-48f9-80de-6f8ee8c55cdb","timestamp":"2026-05-05T14:25:13.610Z","parentId":"a8251e6b-90a8-4931-b3a7-b33934f7059b"}
